@NODE MAIN "Pegase"

                      Pegase : mPEG Audio Stream Encoder
                      ==================================

                         (c) 1998-2000, Didier Levet


    As my native language is french,  and  not  english,  this  documentation
 might  be unreadable for most of you because of some mistakes. Do forgive me
 for that.


@{FG shine}=============================================================================

                                 @{b} DISCLAIMER@{ub}

     NO WARRANTY, IMPLICIT OR EXPLICIT, WILL BE DUE BECAUSE OF THE USE  OF
     THIS  PROGRAMM.  ANY  DAMAGES,  DIRECT  OR  INDIRECT,  CAUSED  BY THE
     INSTALLATION  OR USE OF THIS PROGRAM WILL NOT  BE  IMPUTABLE  TO  THE
     AUTHOR.  YOU,  WHEN INSTALLING THIS SOFTWARE, ASSUME THE LIABILITY OF
     ALL RISKS TIED TO THE INSTALLATION OR USE OF THIS PROGRAM.

=============================================================================@{FG text}

    Pegase  is  an  MPEG  audio  encoder,  optimized  for  680x0/PPC  familly
 processors It needs OS 2.0 or above to run. The PPC version requires WarpOS.

    Due to the @{"patents" link MP3_ROYALTIES} that cover mp3 encoding,  Pegase  will  never  support
 Layer 3. However, the layer 2 algorithm gives really good results in a short
 time, making Pegase usefull for anyone. At least, I hope so.


                               @{" Presentation " Link PREFACE}
                               @{" Distribution " Link DISTRIB}
                               @{" Installation " Link INSTALL}
                               @{" How to use   " Link USE}
                               @{" Future       " Link FUTUR}
                               @{" Problems     " Link PROBLEMS}
                               @{" Support      " Link SUPPORT}
                               @{" History      " Link HISTORY}
                               @{" Thanks       " Link THANKS}


    Pegase is EMail-ware.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PREFACE "Presentation"

                                 @{FG shine}@{b}PRESENTATION@{FG text}@{ub}
                                 @{FG shine}@{b}------------@{FG text}@{ub}

    Although it is based upon the original  version  of  Musicin  (ISO/MPEG),
 only  the principle on which things work is identical. The whole source code
 has been rewritten, with the Amiga spirit in mind, in  order  to  provide  a
 fast encoder without sacrifying the quality.

    The first motivation comes from a simple finding : Musicin PPC appears to
 be  slow compared to the CPU power, so slow that I was convinced that it was
 a quick port which misuse this processor.
    Then, I wanted to show what a foolish 68060 is able to do,  demonstrating
 that  a  PPC  might  be  useless when it is not used as it should be. I must
 admit that the result goes far away than what I expected.


    MPEG files produced with Pegase are better than the ones created with the
 Amiga version of Musicin. But Pegase is a lot faster : Encoding of a  stereo
 AIFF  file,  44.1  KHz,  160  kbits/s,  requires roughly two times the sound
 duration (68060/50). A 68040/40 is able to encode  the  same  file  at  five
 times the sound duration.

    Pegase is able to encode IFF-AIFF, IFF-MAUD  and  RIFF-WAV  files.  These
 files  can  be  mono  or  stereo.  RAW  format, and CDDA (CD Audio) are also
 supported. The samples must be 16 bits wide, and the sample  frequency  must
 be close to 32 KHz, 44.1 KHz or 48 KHz.

    You can create MPEG files using the Layer I  or  the Layer II algorithms.
 Stereo songs can be encoded using the joint-stereo mode.

@ENDNODE

@NODE DISTRIB "Distribution"

                                 @{FG shine}@{b}DISTRIBUTION@{FG text}@{ub}
                                 @{FG shine}@{b}------------@{FG text}@{ub}

 No restrictions apply.

@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "Installation"

                                 @{FG shine}@{b}INSTALLATION@{FG text}@{ub}
                                 @{FG shine}@{b}------------@{FG text}@{ub}

    There is no need for an Installer script, and installation by hand is not
 that difficult. Simply copy Pegase where you want, that's all.

    The default language is english (or something similar to :-)  ).  When  a
 translation  is  available  for  your country, you can also copy the catalog
 file to your LOCALE: directory, as usual.

@ENDNODE

@NODE USE "How to use"

                                  @{FG shine}@{b}HOW TO USE@{FG text}@{ub}
                                  @{FG shine}@{b}----------@{FG text}@{ub}

    Pegase could be run from Shell as well as from Workbench. In both  cases,
 it  examines  its  icon  in  order  to alter the default settings. Then, CLI
 parameters are taken into account and override these settings.

    You can stop Pegase by pressing "@{b}CTRL-C@{ub}" or  "@{b}CTRL-D@{ub}".  The  former  only
 stops  the  file  being  processed.  If  there are some files waiting in the
 queue, Pegase starts to encode the next one. The latter, on the other  side,
 stops  the  whole  process. Remaining files are ignored, and partial encoded
 files are never deleted.


    Pegase only supports one psycho-acoustical analyzer, which is refered to
 as "psycho #2" in Musicin.


 @{FG shine}@{b}Starting from a Shell :@{FG text}@{ub}
 @{FG shine}@{b}-----------------------@{FG text}@{ub}

    Pegase sticks to the standard rules of Shell commands. Options are given
 on the command line.

    As usual, "Pegase ?"  causes  the  Shell  to  display  the  command  line
 pattern.  If you answer this pattern with another question mark, then Pegase
 shows its extended help :

    Usage :
    @{" FROM      " Link FROM} Input sound files or directories to encode.
    @{" TO        " Link TO} Output file name, or destination directory.
    @{" LAYER     " Link LAYER} Layer number (1 or 2). Default = 2.
    @{" FREQ      " Link FREQ} Sampling frequency (Hz). Default = 44100.
    @{" BITRATE   " Link BITRATE} Total bitrate (kbits/s). Default = 160.
    @{" MONO      " Link MONO} Mono encoding.
    @{" JSTEREO   " Link JSTEREO} Joint stereo encoding.
    @{" COPYRIGHT " Link COPYRIGHT} Mark as copyright.
    @{" ORIGINAL  " Link ORIGINAL} Mark as original.
    @{" CRC       " Link CRC} Add error protection.
    @{" PRIORITY  " Link PRIORITY} Change Pegase's priority.
    @{" VERBOSE   " Link VERBOSE} Verbose output.
    @{" MOTOROLA  " Link CDDA_AND_PIPE} Motorola byte order/PIPE switch.
    @{" INTEL     " Link CDDA_AND_PIPE} Motorola byte order/PIPE switch.
    @{" DELETE    " Link AUTODELETE} Delete source file after completion.

    Don't bother about the stack size. Pegase will be happy with a standard 4
 kb stack.


 @{FG shine}@{b}Starting from Workbench :@{FG text}@{ub}
 @{FG shine}@{b}-------------------------@{FG text}@{ub}

    The default settings, as said above, can be changed using the icon's tool
 types :

    @{" TO        " Link TO} Output file name, or destination directory.
    @{" PATTERN   " Link PATTERN} File requester's pattern.
    @{" LAYER     " Link LAYER} Layer number.
    @{" FREQ      " Link FREQ} Sampling frequency.
    @{" BITRATE   " Link BITRATE} Total bitrate.
    @{" MONO      " Link MONO} Mono encoding.
    @{" JSTEREO   " Link JSTEREO} Joint stereo encoding.
    @{" COPYRIGHT " Link COPYRIGHT} Mark as copyright.
    @{" ORIGINAL  " Link ORIGINAL} Mark as original.
    @{" PRIORITY  " Link PRIORITY} Change Pegase's priority.
    @{" CRC       " Link CRC} Add error protection.
    @{" DELETE    " Link AUTODELETE} Delete source file after completion.

    There's also some tool types that allow you to set the  default  settings
 of the file requester :

    @{" FR_SOURCE " Link FileRequester} Default directory.
    @{" FR_XPOS   " Link FileRequester} Default X position.
    @{" FR_YPOS   " Link FileRequester} Default Y position.
    @{" FR_WIDTH  " Link FileRequester} Default width.
    @{" FR_HEIGHT " Link FileRequester} Default height.

    The console settings can be changed with an environment variable named
 "PEGASE_WBCONSOLE". Use the "SetEnv" command to create it, and don't forget
 to copy it to "ENVARC:" to make it permanent when you are done.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FileRequester "File Requester"

 @{FG shine}@{b}File requester@{FG text}@{ub}

    If you start Pegase from the Workbench by clicking on its icon,  or  when
 you  don't  provide  source files on the command line, Pegase pops up a file
 requester. You can select multiple files at once, but they  must  reside  in
 the same directory.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FROM "FROM"

@{FG shine}@{b}FROM : Source(s).@{FG text}@{ub}

    Specify one or more file  and/or  directory  names.  When  no  source  is
 specified,  Pegase open a file requester where you can pick up several files
 at once (multi-selection).

    When one entry, at least, is  a  directory,  Pegase  analyzes  all  files
 inside  this directory, and selects the ones that can be assumed to be audio
 files. This automatic selection is helpful, but it is too simple to be  very
 accurate.  For instance, any unknown file might be assumed to be a RAW audio
 file. Don't expect anything useful if you encode such a file ! ;-)

    Pegase only handles these file formats :

 - AIFF : Mono/stereo, 16 bits, uncompressed.
 - MAUD : Mono/stereo, 16 bits, uncompressed.
 - WAV  : Mono/stereo, 16 bits, uncompressed.
 - CDDA : Always stereo, 16 bits, 44.1 KHz.  The byte order  (Intel/Motorola)
          is determined automatically by some magic.
 - RAW  : Mono, 16 bits  (might be the default format  for  any unknown  file
          type). Motorola byte order is expected for the samples.

    The sampling frequency used by  the  coder  comes  from  the  audio  file
 header's  if  it  is available there (AIFF, MAUD and WAV). CDDA files always
 use 44.1 KHz sampling rate (starting from Pegase  1.85,  you can  select the
 sampling rate with the 'FREQ' keyword).

    Note that only 16 bits sample files are supported. Sample frequency  must
 be  close  to those allowed by the encoder algorithm (32 KHz, 44.1 KHz or 48
 KHz, +/- 4%).

 @{b}@{FG shine}NB@{FG text}@{ub} : The byte order determination is based upon a statistical method  so  it
 can give wrong results in some case.
 See also @{" MOTOROLA/INTEL " link CDDA_AND_PIPE}.

@ENDNODE

@NODE TO "TO"

 @{FG shine}@{b}TO : Destination.@{FG text}@{ub}

    This define the output file name, or the directory where to  save  output
 files.  When  no  destination is given, ouput files are saved along with the
 input files. If a filename extension already exists,  it's  replaced  by  an
 ".mp?" like extension.

    You are not allowed to define an explicit output file name when there are
 multiple  sources. Otherwise, Pegase will go back to its default setting and
 save output files in the source's directory.

    When the destination is a directory, Pegase saves all output files there,
 after  having  replaced  any  existing extension with ".mp?". This extension
 depends on the layer number (".mp1" for layer 1, or ".mp2" for layer 2).
    The original filename extension is not  replaced  if  it  starts  with  a
 decimal digit.

 @{FG shine}@{b}NOTE :@{FG text}@{ub}

    @{i}By now, Pegase doesn't check if it  can  write  the  output  file  before
 starting  the  encoding.  Also,  an  already  existing  destination  file is
 overwritten, without any warning.@{ui}

@ENDNODE

@NODE LAYER "LAYER"

 @{FG shine}@{b}LAYER : Layer number.@{FG text}@{ub}

    By now, Pegase only supports layer level 1 and 2. Layer 2 gives the best
 results, and, despite what you might think, it is faster than layer 1.

    The default setting is layer 2. Layer 3 is not supported.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FREQ "FREQ"

 @{FG shine}@{b}FREQ : Sample frequency.@{FG text}@{ub}

    Pegase use the sample frequency specified  in  the  input  file  header's
 (AIFF, MAUD or WAV), or select 44.1 KHz in case of a CDDA file encoding.

    Then, you only need to define this frequency for RAW format audio  files.
 The sampling rate can also be defined when encoding CDDA files.  This  makes
 no sense when encoding real CD Audio tracks, but this is usefull if you  use
 a frontend that pass sample datas to Pegase through a PIPE.

    In all cases, the sample frequency must be close to 32 KHz, 44.1  KHz  or
 48 KHz (+/- 4%).

@ENDNODE

@NODE BITRATE "BITRATE"

 @{FG shine}@{b}BITRATE : Output bit rate (kbits/s).@{FG text}@{ub}

    This value determines the size (and quality) of the  MPEG  file.  Several
 values are allowed, for each layer.

    The default bitrate (160 kbits/s) gives near-CD  quality  in  most  cases
 (44.1 KHz sampling rate). 48 KHz samples require a higher bitrate.

    You don't need to learn each of these values as the encoder  selects  one
 that  is lowest when the specified value is not allowed. Thus, giving 200 as
 bitrate causes Pegase to select 192 kbits/s.

    Known bitrates are (layer 1/layer 2) :

 32, 64, 96, 128, 160, 192, 224, 256, 288, 320, 352, 384, 416 and 448.
 32, 48, 56,  64,  80,  96, 112, 128, 160, 192, 224, 256, 320 and 384.


    Having the sample frequency and the number of channels, you  can  compute
 the  MPEG  file  size.  In example, for a 35 Mb CDDA file, using 160 kbits/s
 output bitrate, we have :

 Source :
 44100  x         16        x     2     = 1411200 bits/s
 (freq)   (bits per sample)   (channel)

 1411200 / 160000  = 8.82 (ratio)
          (bitrate)

 35 x 1024˛ / 8.82 = 3.97 Mb = Output file size.


    The bitrate has no  noticeable  effect  on  the  encoding  speed.  Slower
 bitrates give a slightly extra speed, but that's all.

@ENDNODE

@NODE MONO "MONO"

 @{FG shine}@{b}MONO : RAW file format.@{FG text}@{ub}

    As RAW files are assumed to be mono files, this option does  nothing  for
 now.

@ENDNODE

@NODE JSTEREO "JSTEREO"

 @{FG shine}@{b}JSTEREO : Use Joint-Stereo mode.@{FG text}@{ub}

    Input file(s) must be stereo. This  option  gives  some  liberty  to  the
 encoder,  which  can  progressively  mix samples to mono on a subband basis.
 Thus, the coder gets more bits to encode  the  samples,  which  improve  the
 quality when you use a (too) low bitrate.

    This mix is done dynamically, for each frame, whenever it  is  necessary.
 The  number  of  mixed  subbands  varied  also from frame to frame, and some
 frames can be encoded in full stereo mode.  Then,  your  decoder/player  can
 forget to tell you that there are some j-stereo frames in the MPEG file.

@ENDNODE

@NODE COPYRIGHT "COPYRIGHT"

 @{FG shine}@{b}COPYRIGHT : Mark as copyright.@{FG text}@{ub}

    This is an information telling that the audio stream is copyrighted.

@ENDNODE

@NODE ORIGINAL "ORIGINAL"

 @{FG shine}@{b}ORIGINAL : Mark as original.@{FG text}@{ub}

    This is an information telling that the audio stream is original.

@ENDNODE

@NODE CRC "CRC"

 @{FG shine}@{b}CRC : Add error protection.@{FG text}@{ub}

    Compute a checksum of each MPEG headers.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PRIORITY "PRIORITY"

 @{FG shine}@{b}PRIORITY : Change Pegase's priority.@{FG text}@{ub}

    Priority values must be in the range [-128; 5].

@ENDNODE

@NODE VERBOSE "VERBOSE"

 @{FG shine}@{b}VERBOSE : Verbose output.@{FG text}@{ub}

    Display global settings.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PATTERN "PATTERN"

 @{FG shine}@{b}PATTERN : File requester pattern.@{FG text}@{ub}

    Define the pattern used to display files in the file requester.

    Default setting : ~(#?.info)

@ENDNODE

@NODE CDDA_AND_PIPE "CDDA byte order and PIPEs"

 @{FG shine}@{b}MOTOROLA : Motorola byte order.@{FG text}@{ub}

    This switch forces @{b}ALL@{ub} input files to be handled as 16-bit  stereo files,
 in which samples are recorded in Big Endian mode (Motorola).

 @{FG shine}@{b}INTEL : Intel byte order.@{FG text}@{ub}

    This switch forces @{b}ALL@{ub} input files to be handled as 16-bit  stereo files,
 in which samples are recorded in Little Endian mode (Intel).

 @{b}@{FG shine}PIPE support :@{FG text}@{ub}

    If you use one of the switches  mentionned  above,  Pegase  bypasses  its
 automatic file type recognition in order to allow you to encode files from a
 PIPE. The 'FREQ' keyword may be used to select the sampling rate.

@ENDNODE

@NODE AUTODELETE "DELETE"

 @{FG shine}@{b}DELETE : Delete source file after completion.@{FG text}@{ub}

    This switch tells Pegase to  delete  the  source  file  after it has been
 successfully encoded.

@ENDNODE

@NODE PROBLEMS "Problems"

                                  @{FG shine}@{b}PROBLEMS@{FG text}@{ub}
                                  @{FG shine}@{b}--------@{FG text}@{ub}


 - Output files overwrite silently existing files.
 - Pegase doesn't check if it can write to the destination file or directory.
   Thus,  encoding something from a CD requires that you define  explicitly a
   destination ("TO" option or Tooltype).
 - Pegase doesn't check if there is enough room on the destination medium  to
   store the MPEG file. Anyway, this detection would prevent the usage of the
   RAM disk as a destination medium.
 - RAW files are assumed to use the MOTOROLA byte order.

   As of today, MPEGA 3.4 (along with mpega.library) refuses  to  handle  any
 file encoded using Layer 1. Despite that, these files  are  perfectly  MPEG-
 compliant, and an older version of MPEGA (v3.3, Aminet Set 6d)  handle  them
 just fine.

@ENDNODE

@NODE FUTUR "Future"

                                    @{FG shine}@{b}FUTURE@{FG text}@{ub}
                                    @{FG shine}@{b}------@{FG text}@{ub}

   "pegase.library" is on its way. It would combine an enhanced encoder and a
 decoder in the same library, but I don't promise anything.
   I don't have any particular motivation to  achieve  this  project,  mainly
 because I just do it for the fun. Believe it or not, I never  use  any  MPEG
 audio related tools and this may explain a lot of things...

@ENDNODE

